{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538652"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:30:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:30:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16258"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16258"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.04,0.39,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8949"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88034"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8949"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16258"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72242"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2112"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"3902"},{"type":"tags","id":"4101"},{"type":"tags","id":"4103"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"9330"},{"type":"tags","id":"9331"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12962"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21290"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39354"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43624"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46198"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88034"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman is reviewed in the General Practice clinic following an incidental finding on a pelvic ultrasound performed during investigation of urinary symptoms. She has no gynaecological symptoms. Her medical history includes severe chronic obstructive pulmonary disease requiring home oxygen, congestive cardiac failure, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and chronic kidney disease. Her medications include tiotropium, salbutamol, furosemide, metformin, and aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The ultrasound shows a 3 cm simple ovarian cyst that is unilocular with thin walls and no solid components. Cancer antigen 125 is 12 kU/L (0-35), carcinoembryonic antigen is 2.2 \u00b5g/L (0-4.7), and cancer antigen 19-9 is 15 kU/L (0-37).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat ultrasound in three months with tumour markers","laparotomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy","Conservative management only","laparoscopic oophorectomy","laparoscopic cystectomy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents an incidentally discovered simple ovarian cyst in a woman with significant medical comorbidities. The cyst demonstrates benign characteristics: it is small (3 cm), unilocular, thin-walled, without solid components, and all tumour markers are normal. These features indicate a very low risk of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound in three months with tumour markers\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. This approach allows monitoring for any concerning changes while avoiding unnecessary surgical intervention in a high-risk patient. Many simple cysts will resolve spontaneously, and those that persist without concerning changes can continue to be monitored.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparotomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would carry significant risks given the patient\u0027s severe comorbidities and is not indicated for a small, simple cyst with normal tumour markers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management only\u003C/strong\u003E without follow-up imaging is inadequate as it would not detect any concerning changes that might develop over time. While the risk is low, some monitoring is prudent in postmenopausal women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic oophorectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be unnecessarily aggressive given the benign characteristics of the cyst and the patient\u0027s significant comorbidities. The risks of surgery and anaesthesia outweigh any potential benefits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E Cystectomy should never be performed in a postmenopausal women if there is concern for ovarian cyst. Oophorectomy should be performed if there is concern for ovarian malignancy to avoid any risk of cyst rupture or spill. Given the patient\u0027s severe cardiopulmonary disease, any surgical intervention carries significant risks that are not justified by the clinical findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to management is recognising when conservative management is appropriate based on cyst characteristics, tumour markers, and patient factors. Current evidence supports surveillance for simple cysts less than 5 cm in postmenopausal women when tumour markers are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Risk of malignancy in simple ovarian cysts is very low when they are unilocular, thin-walled, and without solid components.","Comorbidities and patient factors should be considered when deciding between surveillance and surgical management of ovarian cysts."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Ovarian cysts in postmenopausal women (Green-top Guideline No. 34) [Internet]. London: RCOG; 2016 [cited 2024 Nov 23]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/ovarian-cysts-in-postmenopausal-women-green-top-guideline-no-34/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72242"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16258"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72242"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-28T19:25:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T19:26:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8949"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88034"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position